column168: Description Of Events

THIS SHIPMENT WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING DURING THE SORTING OPERATION. THE INNER GLASS CONTAINER BROKE INSIDE THE PACKAGING WHEN THIS PACKAGE FELL TO THE GROUND AND OTHER PACKAGES FELL ON TOP OF IT.  SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED AND ASKED THAT IT BE RETURNED.

THIS SHIPMENT WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING DURING THE SORTING OPERATION AS A RESULT OF THE PACKAGE FALLING FROM THE SORT BELT TO THE GROUND.  THE INNER GLASS CONTAINER WAS BROKEN AND LEAKED.  THE PACKAGE WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND THE SHIPPER WAS LATER CONTACTED REGARDING DISPOSITION.

WHILE IN THE FACILITY, ONE DAMAGED FIFTY POUND PAPER BAG WAS DISCOVERED ON A PALLET CONTAINING FOUR, FIFTY POUND PAPER BAGS. THE DAMAGE TO THE BAG WAS DUE TO AN UNKNOWN CAUSE. APPROXIMATELY HALF A POUND OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. FACILITY PERSONNEL PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES, ABSORBENT PADS, A DUSTPAN AND A WHISK BROOM. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND DAMAGED BAG WERE PLACED INTO A THIRTY-FIVE GALLON STEEL RECOVERY DRUM WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE FACILITY AWAITING DISPOSITION. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: DURING DELIVERY PROCESS, THE DRIVER WAS SWITCHING TANKS AND PRODUCT BEGAN TO LEAK FROM THE DELIVERY HOSE. MAJORITY OF SPILL WENT INTO A CONTAINMENT DYKE, HOWEVER ABOUT ONE GALLON SPILLED AND WAS CONTAINED ONTO THE CONCRETE. SPILLED PRODUCT WAS IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP.

SAFETY-KLEEN EMPLOYEES AT A CUSTOMER LOCATION ATTEMPTED TO MOVE ONE 55 GALLON METAL DRUM FOR LOADING.  WHILE PREPARING THE DRUM FOR TRANSPORT, THE WELD SEALED SEAM ON THE CONTAINER SPLIT RELEASING 50 GALLONS OF ETHANOL/WATER MIX INTO SECONDARY CONTAINMENT.  THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY ABSORBED USING ABSORBENT PADS WHICH WERE CONTAINERIZED, ALONG WITH THE SPILL CLEAN UP MATERIALS INTO ONE 55 GALLON DRUM.  THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY 650 POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 1021 BERRYESSA ROAD IN SAN JOSE, CALIFORNIA FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL.  THE EMPLOYEES WERE COUNSELED ON PROPER DRUM INSPECTION AND LOADING TECHNIQUES TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.
SEAM RELAXED AND SEEPAGE BEGAN.  LEAK WAS DISCOVER BEFORE MUCH OF PRODUCT LEAKED FROM PACKAGE - ABSORBENT MATERIAL APPLIED AND CLEANUP WAS IMPLEMENTED EXPEDITIOUSLY.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE TRAVELING WESTBOUND ON INTERSTATE 70 AT MILE MARKER 190, THE TRAILER AND ITS CONTENTS CAUGHT FIRE.  APPROXIMATELY FORTY-TWO THOUSAND POUNDS OF PRODUCT BURNED AND MELTED THROUGH THE TRAILER FLOOR AND ONTO THE SHOULDER OF THE ROAD.  UPON INSPECTION, IT APPEARED THAT THE RIGHT REAR WHEEL BEARING ON THE TRAILER HAD FAILED.  THE MOAB CITY FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THE UTAH STATE POLICE RESPONDED TO THE SCENE TO CONTAIN THE FIRE AND TO CLOSE THE INTERSTATE.  T.W. COMPANY OF SALT LAKE CITY, UT WAS CONTACTED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP.  THE CONTRACTOR GENERATED FOUR ROLL-OFF BOXES OF PRODUCT, TRAILER PARTS, AND DIRT, WHICH WERE DISPOSED OF THROUGH EAST CARBON DEVELOPMENT CORPORATION OF SALT LAKE CITY, UT.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSED WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.  ALL FEDERAL, STATE AND LOCAL REGULATORY AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED.

column168: ON SUNDAY THE MARCH 10TH 14 X 5 GALLON CARBOYS CONTAINING PHOSPHORIC ACID AND WATER WERE PICKED UP FOR DISPOSAL FROM PRINCESS CRUISES IN SANTA CLARITA, CA. THESE 14 CARBOYS WERE PLACED ON A PALLET AND LOADED ONTO A TRUCK FOR TRANSPORTATION TO THE DESIGNATED TERMINAL. THE CARBOYS WERE DOUBLE STACKED (CARBOYS ARE DESIGNED TO INTERLOCK AS THEY GET DOUBLE STACKED) AND SHRINK WRAPPED TO THE PALLET. EACH LAYER WAS SECURED AGAINST MOVEMENT OFF THE PALLET. THIS PALLET WAS THEN BRACED WITH A NYLON STRAP TO THE TRUCK TO PREVENT MOVEMENT DURING TRANSPORTATION. ON MARCH 11,2002, WHILE BEING IN THE TERMINAL, IT WAS MOVED OFF THE PALLET AND FALLEN TO THE SIDE. ONE OF THESE CARBOYS HAD A CRACKED LID AND THAT IS WHAT CAUSED THE SPILL. IT WAS ESTIMATED THAT ABOUT 2.5 GALLONS OF THE MATERIAL WAS SPILLED. THE SPILLED AREA WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP WITH SODIUM BI-CARBONATE AND DECONTAMINATED. PH VERIFICATION WAS OBTAINED TO ENSURE THE EFFECTIVENESS OF THE DECONTAMINATION PROCESS. THE CRACKED LID ON THE CARBOY WAS REPLACED WITH A NEW ONE. THE CARBOYS WERE RE-STACKED ON THE PALLET AND SECURED WITH A POLY STRAP BY ENSURING THAT EACH ROW WAS TIED OFF TO THE PALLET. THE CARBOYS WERE THEN SHRINK WRAPPED TO THE PALLET. THE PALLET INSTEAD OF BEING LOADED ALL THE WAY AT THE BACK END OF THE TRAILER WAS PLACED STRATEGICALLY BETWEEN THE OTHER CONTAINERS(55-GALLONS SIZE) ON THE TRAILER TO PREVENT MOVEMENT IN ALL 4 DIRECTIONS.

THE SHIPMENT CONSISTED OF THREE CARDBOARD BOXES. TWO OF THESE BOXES CONTAINED TWO SMALLER CARDBOARD BOXES INSIDE. EACH SMALLER CARDBOARD BOX CONTAINED A TOTAL OF 12 PLASTIC CANSITERS EACH WITH 200 MEDICAL WIPES IMPREGNATED IN ISOPROPYL ALCOHOL. THE EXTERNAL BOXES HAD NO ORIENTATION OR HANDLING LABELS. WHILE LOADING THE BOXES AT MIAMI AIRPORT, ONE EMMITTED A STRONG ALCOHOL ODOR AND WAS NOT LOADED. ON THIS BOX, ONE CANISTER TOP HAD BURSTED OPENED AND RELEASED THE ISOPROPYL ALCOHOL WHICH WAS MOSTLY ABSORBED BY THE TWO CARDBOARD BOXES WHICH HELD THE CANISTERS. NO SIGNS OF DAMAGE DUE TO FALL, HIT, STRUCK OR RAMMING WAS VISIBLE ON THE BOXES. CARGO ENVIRONMENTAL COORDINATORS AND SECURITY AND ENVIRONMENTAL OFFICER RESPONDED TO THE FINDING. MSDS WAS REQUESTED FROM MANUFACTURER.

column168: OUR DRIVER HAD TAKEN HIS EIGHT-HOUR BREAK AT THE TRUCK STOP AT 108 HWY 397. PRIOR TO LEAVING HE WAS DOING HIS PRE-TRIP INSPECTION AND DISCOVERED THAT THERE WAS A SMALL LEAK AROUND THE EXTERNAL VALVE ASSEMBLY. THIS ASSEMBLY IS ON THE RIGHT REAR FENDER OF THE TRAILER, AND IT WAS LEAKING HYDROCHLORIC ACID ONTO THE FENDER. THE LIQUID THAT WAS DRIPPING ONTO THE FENDER WAS ALSO FUMING. AFTER DISCOVERING THIS LEAK OUR DRIVER NOTIFIED OUR SAFETY DEPARTMENT AND CONTACTED HIS TERMINAL MANAGE THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE WERE NOTIFIED AND THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER WAS CALLED. SERVICE TRANSPORT CO. CALLED ASCO ENVIRONMENTAL OF LAKE CHARLES, LA. TO RESPOND AND CONTAIN THE DRIPPING ACID. THE ACID DID NOT DRIP ONTO THE ASPHALT PARKING LOT OF THE TRUCKSTOP. IT WAS CONTAINED ON THE FENDER OF THE TRAILER AND CLEANED OFF BY ASCO ENVIRONMENTAL. THE VALVE WAS REMOVED AND THE LINE WAS BLOCKED OFF WITH A BLANK FLANGE.  AFTER THE CLEANUP THE DRIVER AND UNIT WERE GIVEN THE OK TO LEAVE AND PROCEED ON TO DESTINATION. THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK WAS A CRACK IN THE VALVE PIPING CAUSED BY IMPROPER INSTALLATION PROPERLY. THERE WAS LESS THAN A PINT OF PRODUCT DRIPPED ONTO THE FENDER AND IT EVAPORATED OR DRIED BEFORE IT COULD DRIP TO PARKING LOT SURFACE.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING, ONE LEAKING FIFTY-FIVE GALLON METAL DRUM WAS DISCOVERED AT THE HALLWAY MARK OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY ONE PINT OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED AND AFFECTED SOME OF THE SURROUNDING DUNNAGE. THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A LOOSE BUNG. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION, AMPHOMAG AND ABSORBENT PADS.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND AFFECTED DUNNAGE WERE PLACED INTO A FIFTEEN GALLON POLY RECOVERY DRUM WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE LOOSE BUNG WAS TIGHTENED AND THE DRUM WAS FORWARDED ON TO THE CONSIGNEE ALONG WITH THE DISPOSITION. THE LOOSE BUNG WAS TIGHTENED THE DRUM WAS FORWARDED ON TO THE CONSIGNEE ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES  WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING, SIX  WET CARTONS EACH CONTAINING ONE, ONE GALLON PLASTIC JUG WERE DISCOVERED AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THREE, ONE GALLON JUGS WERE DAMAGED AND THE REMAINING THREE WERE UNAFFECTED. APPROXIMATELY THREE GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. THE DAMAGE TO THE JUGS WAS DUE TO BEING CRUSHED BY HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON TOP. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES AND ABSORBENT PADS. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, THREE WET CARTONS AND THREE DAMAGED JUGS WERE PLACED INTO A FOURTEEN GALLON PLASTIC  RECOVERY DRUM WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE THREE AFFECTED CARTONS WERE CLEANED OFF AND WILL BE FORWARDED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING, ONE DAMAGED, FIVE GALLON STEEL PAIL WAS DISCOVERED AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY THREE GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. THE DAMAGE TO THE PAIL WAS DUE TO A PUNCTURE DURING LOADING. TERMINAL PERSONNEL PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES AND ABSORBENT RAGS. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND DAMAGED PAIL WERE PLACED INTO AN EIGHT GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM. THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL TO SEE IF THE CONSIGNEE WILL ACCEPT THE SHIPMENT. NO INJURIES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

CN CARMAN WHILE INSPECTING TRACK#4 FOUND TANK CAR GATX LEAKING AT THE STUB SILL ON THE "B" END OF THE CAR. ALL APPROPRIATE DEPARTMENTS WERE NOTIFIED AND CN HAZMAT RESPONSE TEAM RESPONDED TO THE AREA. TEAM FOUND CRACK IN WELL AT THE STUB STILL AND UP INTO THE TANK. LEAK WAS SLOWED TO A DRIP USING PETRO PUTTY ON CRACKS. PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED TO TRUCKS AND CAR WILL BE HOME SHOPPED FOR REPAIR.

column168: CN CARMAN DOING INSPECTION OF CARS IN TRACK #17 FOUND TANK CAR SCMX 4309 LEAKING FROM BOTTOM OUTLET. ALL APPROPRIATE DEPARTMENTS NOTIFIED AND CN HAZMAT RESPONSE TEAM RESPONDED. TEAM FOUND THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE PART WAY OPEN WITH HANDLE NOT IN HOLDER NOR LOCKING PIN IN PLACE. TEAM CLOSED VALVE AND PUT LOCKING PIN IN PLACE AND LEAK STOPPED. CAR OKAY FOR MOVEMENT.

column168: DRUM CAME IN DENTED ON SIDE LEAKING AT A DRAIN PLUG.

DURING A ROUTINE INSPECTION WHILE STOPPED OFF HIGHWAY 90 & 287 WESTBOUND AT MILE MARKER 273, THE FORWARD AIR, INC. DRIVER DISCOVERED A LEAK IN THE BACK OF THE TRAILER. APPARENTLY A PALLET HAD BROKE IN THE TRAILER CAUSING TWO (2) FIVE GALLON PAILS TO FALL AND POP THEIR LIDS. APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED INSIDE THE TRAILER. OLYMPUS TECHNICAL SERVICES, INC. OF HELENA, MONTANA RESPONDED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. OLYMPUS TECHNICAL SERVICES, INC. APPLIED FLOOR DRY TO THE FREE PRODUCT ON THE TRAILER FLOOR. THE TWO (2) DAMAGED 5- GALLON PAILS WERE PLACED INTO TWO (2) TWENTY-GALLON OVERPACK DRUMS ALONG WITH THE CONTAMINATED FLOOR DRY. TWO (2) TWENTY-GALLON OVERPACK DRUMS WERE PLACED BACK ON THE FORWARD AIR, INC. TRAILER TO BE SENT ON TO THEIR DESTINATION. NO ADDITIONAL RESPONSE PLANS EXIST AT THIS  TIME. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES  REPORTED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE AT THE BAX GLOBAL, INC. FACILITY IN SWANTON, OHIO, ONE, TWENTY LITER STEEL DRUM WAS PUNCTURED BY A FORKLIFT. APPROXIMATELY ONE LITER OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. BAX GLOBAL, INC. PERSONNEL PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES AND ABSORBENTS. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND DAMAGED DRUM WERE PLACED INTO A FIFTY-FIVE GALLON STEEL OVERPACK DRUM, WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column42: FIRE EXTINGUISHERS CONTAINING COMPRESSED OR LIQUEFIED GAS
column168: DURING A ROUTINE INSPECTION OF A PALLET THAT WAS JUST REMOVED FROM AN AIRCRAFT A WHITE POWDER WAS DISCOVERED. UPON INVESTIGATION IT WAS DISCOVERED THE RELEASE WAS COMING FROM A CARTON CONTAINING A FIRE EXTINGUISHER. APPROXIMATELY TWO POUNDS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A DEFECTIVE EXTINGUISHER. TERMINAL PERSONNEL PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, CARTON AND LEAKING EXTINGUISHER WERE PLACED INTO A FIFTY-FIVE GALLON STEEL RECOVERY DRUM WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE FACILITY FOR DISPOSITION. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

OUTBOUND DRIVER REPORTED CONTAINER LEAKING PRODUCT & IT WAS TAKEN TO CONTAINMENT AREA. CONTRACT RESPONDERS FOUND  ONE STEEL DRUM ON SECOND TIER, THIRD ROW FROM REAR WITH A DEFECTIVE BOTTOM CHIME (DRUM SIDE WALL FOLDED OVER IN CHIME). DEFECTIVE DRUM PLACED INTO OVERPACK DRUM & LEFT BEHIND FOR SHIPPER INSTRUCTIONS. SPILLED PRODUCT CLEANED FROM CONTAINER & OTHER DRUMS. REMOVED DRUMS RETURNED TO LOAD & CONTAINER RELEASED TO PROCEED TO DESTINATION AFTERWARDS.

INBOUND TRAIN INSPECTION REVEALED PRODUCT VENTING FROM VALVE/CONTROL CABINET & TANK CAR ISOLATED IN YARD. PINHOLE LEAKS DISCOVERED AT SAMPLE VALVE BASE  WELD. SHIPPER TRANSFERRED PRODUCT TO TANKER TRUCKS WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT. RESIDUE TANK CAR SENT TO QUALIFIED REPAIR FACILITY FOR REPAIRS.

column168: INBOUND TRAIN INSPECTION REVEALED PRODUCT ODOR EMANATING FROM CAR. BNSF RESPONDER FOUND THE UNLOADING CONNECTION BALL VALVE HANDLE IN OPEN POSITION & VALVE HANDLE STEM PACKING NUT LOOSE THAT ALLOWED PRODUCT TO SEEP FROM IT. VALVE CLOSED & PACKING NUT TOO TIGHTENED ELIMINATION RELEASE. APPEARED 4 INCH BALL VALVE RECENTLY REPLACED & VALVE POSITION WOULD NOT ALLOW HANDLE CLEARANCE WHEN PROTECTIVE HOUSING COVER CLOSED. HANDLE LEFT OFF & SECURED INSIDE HOUSING.

column168: DURING SWITCHING IN YARD, CAR REPORTED LEAKING PRODUCT FROM FILL HOLE AREA. CONTRACT RESPONDERS FOUND FILL HOLE GASKET DETERIORATED, CRACKED, OUT OF SHAPE & MISALIGNED. NEW GASKET APPLIED, FILL HOLE SECURED & NO FURTHER PRODUCT RELEASE NOTED.  RESPONDERS NEUTRALIZED SPILLED PRODUCT ON TANK SHELL & CAR RELEASED TO PROCEED TO DESTINATION. AT INCIDENT PHASE A BNSF EMPLOYEE HAD PRODUCT SPLASH ON THEIR CLOTHING ONLY WITH NO SKIN CONTACT OR INJURY RESULTING.

NEW GASKET APPLIED & MANWAY BOLTS TOOL TIGHTENED, ELIMINATING PRODUCT ODOR. CAR RELEASED TO DESTINATION AFTER NO FURTHER PRODUCT RELEASE EVIDENT.

column168: ETCX 223511 WAS INVOLVED IN A DERAILMENT WHICH RESULTED IN THE LEADING TRUCKS BEING SHOVED BACK UNDERNEATH THE TANK CAR. THE TRUCKS SHEARED OFF THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE ASSEMBLY AND MOVED THE INTERNAL OUTLET VALVE OPERATING HANDLE TO THE OPEN POSITION ALLOWING THE CONTENTS TO ESCAPE. THE REMAINING CONTENTS OF THE CAR WERE PUMPED INTO CONTAINERS. THE CAUSE OF THE DERAILMENT REMAINS UNDER INVESTIGATION. ENVIRONMENTAL CLEAN-UP OPERATIONS ARE CONTINUING UNDER THE GUIDANCE OF LOCAL AND STATE AUTHORITIES.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: T/C GATX-71067, LOAD WASTE PHENOL SOLUTIONS, WAS DETECTED TO HAVE A CHEMICAL ODOR COMING FROM CAR BY A CSXT CAR INSPECTOR WHILE CONDUCTING AN INBOUND INSPECTION. CAR WAS ISOLATED AND AN ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR WAS NOTIFIED. THE CONTRACTOR FOUND THAT THE BOLTS ON THE MANWAY LID WERE LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT. THE LOOSE MANWAY LID ALLOWED VAPORS TO ESCAPE FROM THE CAR THUS CAUSING THE NOXIOUS ODOR. A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID PRODUCT WAS DETECTED ON THE MANWAY LID HINGE AND WAS REMOVED USING ABSORBENT PADS. THE CONTRACTOR TIGHTENED THE MANWAY BOLTS AND THE ODOR FROM THE CAR CEASED.THE CAR WAS THEN COUPLED TO A LOCOMOTIVE AND MOVED BACK AND FORTH TO VERIFY SECUREMENT OF MANWAY AND NO LEAKAGE WAS DETECTED. CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT TO CONSIGNEE.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: T/C GATX-4661, LOAD HAZARDOUS WASTE, LIQUID N.O.S., WAS NOTED TO SPLASH LIQUID FROM TOP OF CAR DURING SWITCHING OPERATIONS. CAR ISOLATED AND AN ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONSE CONTRACTOR WAS NOTIFIED. THE CONTRACTOR FOUND THE MANWAY LID BOLTS WERE LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT. DURING THEIR INSPECTION OF THE MANWAY CLOSURE, THE ALSO FOUND THAT THE MANWAY LID GASKET WAS DETERIORATED AND CRACKED. THE CONTRACTOR REPLACED THE MANWAY LID GASKET AND RE-SECURED THE LID. THE CAR WAS THEN COUPLED TO A LOCOMOTIVE AND MOVED BACK AND FORTH TO CHECK FOR LEAKAGE. NO FURTHER LEAKAGE WAS DETECTED AND CAR WAS RELEASED.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing; Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: WHEN TRAILER WAS OPENED UP TO UNLOAD TRAILER THE DSR DISCOVERED THAT THE SHIPMENT HAD FALLEN OVER AND 8 BOTTLES IN ONE CARTON WERE BROKEN.  CLEAN-UP BY FOS. INFORMATION WILL BE SENT BACK TO ORIGIN SERVICE CENTER.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: VEHICLE #1 WAS GOING NORTH ON AL79 AT ABOUT 45 MPH. VEHICLE #2 ALSO GOING NORTH PASSED #1 AND AS #2 WAS COMPLETING HIS PASS HE SLAMMED ON HIS BRAKES. #1 NOT KNOWING WHAT WAS GOING ON SLAMMED ON HIS BRAKES TO AVOID # 2. # 1 WAS ALMOST STOPPED WHEN HIS RIGHT TRAILER WHEELS SLIPPED OFF THE PAVEMENT (NO SHOULDER) AND HIS VEHICLE ROLLED INTO THE DITCH. ABOUT TRAILER. THE ROAD WAS CLOSED FOR SEVERAL HOURS AND SEVERAL FAMILIES WERE EVACUATED UNTIL THE TRANSFER WAS COMPLETED. VEHICLE # 2 TRIED TO STOP BECAUSE A PREVIOUS VEHICLE HAD TORN DOWN THE OVERHEAD POWER LINES AND THEY WERE LAYING ON THE ROAD.

EMPLOYEE WAS UNLOADING FREIGHT FROM THE TRAILER AND WENT INTO A PALLET WITH A FORKLIFT TRUCK. THE PALLET IN FRONT OF THE DRUM OF COMPOUND CLEANING LIQUID WAS SMALLER THAN THE BLADES OF THE FORKLIFT & THE EMPLOYEE FAILED TO USE CAUTION AND DID FAIL TO FOLLOW COMPANY PROCEDURES REGARDING THE SAFE HANDLING OF FREIGHT (AS TRAINED IN THE SAFE HANDLING OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS & POWERED INDUSTRIAL LIFT TRUCK TRAINING) AND ALLOWED HIS FORKS TO PUNCTURE THE DRUM. THE EMPLOYEE WILL BE RE-TRAINED.

A CLEAN-UP CONTRACTOR WAS CALLED TO CLEAN-UP SITE WITH APPROVAL OF LINCOLN COUNTY EPA.

column62: Overfilled; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: DRIVER ASKED ME TO LOOK AT PRODUCT. PRODUCT WAS LEAKING FROM TOP AROUND A SPOUT OR VALVE CAP. THE PRODUCT WAS JUST DRIPPING A SMALL AMOUNT. I CALLED THE EMERGENCY CONTACT AND THEY HAD NALCO CALL ME. DAVE COLBY WITH NALCO ASKED ME TO TIGHTEN THE CAP AND MOVE TO DEST. THIS WAS DONE. I PUT THE CLEAN UP RAGS AND OIL DRY IN A CONTAINMENT BUCKET.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: DRIVER PULLED AWAY FROM CUSTOMERS DOCK WITHOUT VERIFYING THE INTEGRITY OF THE LOAD. FREIGHT SHIFTED WHILE IN TRANSIT. RESULTING IN 1 DRUM FALLING OVER AND BEING PUNCTURED ON ANOTHER PIECE OF FREIGHT CONTAINING STEEL. WE CURRENTLY EMPLOY STRICT GUIDELINES WHEN HANDLING DRUMS, HOWEVER THESE WERE NOT FOLLOWED ON THIS OCCASION AND THE DRIVER WILL BE COUNSELED.

AT POINT OF PICKUP THE COURIER NOTICED A FLAMMABLE LIQUID LABEL ON THE PACKAGE BUT NO DANGEROUS GOODS MARKINGS OR DECLARATION PAPERWORK. THIS WAS A PICKUP AT THE CUSTOMER SITE AND THEY WERE AVAILABLE SO THE COURIER ASKED IF THIS WAS A DANGEROUS GOODS SHIPMENT. THE COURIER WAS TOLD IT WAS A RE-USED BOX AND DID NOT CONTAIN DANGEROUS GOODS. THE HAZARD LABEL WAS REMOVED FROM THE SHIPMENT AND THE COURIER CONTINUED HER ROUTE. SHE NOTICED AN ODOR SOON THEREAFTER AND FELT ILL. THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AS IT APPEARED TO BE THIS SHIPMENT THAT EXHIBITED THE ODOR. THE SHIPPER OFFERED TO ACCEPT THE PACKAGE AND THE COURIER DELIVERED IT BACK TO THEM. THE COURIER WAITED FOR THE CUSTOMER TO CHECK OUT THEIR SHIPMENT. WHEN THEY REMOVED THE INNER CONTENTS IT SAID "FLAMMABLE LIQUID:" ON THE INNER PACKAGE.THE COURIER TRIED TO EXPLAIN THE SERIOUSNESS OF THIS OFFENSE. LATER, WHEN FEDEX SAFETY WAS NOTIFIED, ONE OF THE SR SAFETY SPECIALISTS FROM OUR DEPARTMENT SPOKE WITH THIS COMPANY. HE PLACED THEM ON OUR EMBARGO LIST FOR ALL BOX FREIGHT UNTIL SUCH TIME AS THEY CAN PROVE DANGEROUS GOODS TRAINING AND CAN PROVIDE A WRITTEN ACTION PLAN TO PREVENT THEIR TENDERING OF UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS ON ALL FUTURE SHIPMENTS. FAA AGENT MARK GENTILE WAS NOTIFIED. AS THE PACKAGE HAD ALREADY BEEN RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER BEFORE FEDEX SAFETY WAS NOTIFIED, WE WERE UNABLE TO HOLD THE SHIPMENT FOR THE FAA INVESTIGATION. THIS IS AN AMENDED 5800 AS THE FIRST ONE I SENT IN HAD A DATE ONE MONTH IN ADVANCE IN ERROR.

THIS SHIPMENT WAS IN FEDEX WAREHOUSE WHEN IT WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING. STANDARD SPILL CLEANUP PROCEDURES OCCURRED AND THE PACKAGE WAS CONTAINED IN A SALVAGE DRUM PENDING DISPOSITION. ALTHOUGH RQ WAS INDICATED ON THE SHIPMENT, AND RQ AMOUNT DID NO SPILL. THE RQ FOR THIS ITEM IS 100 KG AND ONLY 90 ML LEAKED.

column168: THIS SHIPMENT WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING WHILE IN THE FEDEX WAREHOUSE. STANDARD SPILL CLEANUP PROCEDURES WERE FOLLOWED AND THE PACKAGE WAS CONTAINED IN A SALVAGE DRUM PENDING FINAL DISPOSITION.

column168: UPON ARRIVAL AT DESTINATION THE DRIVER NOTICED SOME MATERIAL ON THE BACK OF THE TANK. HE IMMEDIATELY CLEANED THE TANKER OFF THEN DROPPED IT AT THE FACILITY. UPON BACK TRACKING HIS TRAVELED ROUTE HE NOTICED TWO SPOTS OF PRODUCT ON THE HILL LEAVING GERMANTOWN. IT WAS CLEANED UP AND PROPERLY DISPOSED OFF. AFTER INSPECTING THE TANKER IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE GASKET IN THE BACK DONE CAP WAS BAD THEREFORE CAUSING THE CAP NOT TO SEAL PROPERLY. THE GASKET WAS REPLACED. NRC REPORT#595760

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: CWX DOCK EMPLOYEE WAS UNLOADING THE NALCO 45' TRAILER IN WHICH NALCO LOADED AT THEIR LOCATION FOR CWX. DOCK EMPLOYEE DISCOVERED WHAT LOADED LIKE A VERY SMALL LEAK WHEN HE REMOVED THIS PLASTIC PAIL FROM THE TRAILER. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THERE WAS A PIN-SIZED HOLE ON THE BOTTOM OF THIS PLASTIC PAIL. APPROXIMATELY 0.25 OUNCES OF PRODUCT LEAKED OUT OF THE PAIL. THE TRAILER WAS IMMEDIATELY INSPECTED FOR NAILS OR ANYTHING ON TO HE FLOOR THAT COULD HAVE BEEN THE CAUSE OF THE HOLE-NOTHING WAS FOUND. DOCK EMPLOYEE AND SHIFT SUPERVISOR PLACED PAIL IN A RECOVERY DRUM, AND CALLED THE SHIPPERS EMERGENCY NUMBER. RECOVERY DRUM IS CURRENTLY SITTING IN OSD AREA OF CON-WAY DOCK AWAITING DISPOSITION FROM THE SHIPPER. SHIPPER WILL MOST LIKELY TAKE BACK THE PAIL AND DISPOSE OF THEMSELVES.

column168: MATERIALS TRUCK WAS RETURNING BACK TO WILLISTON ND., WHEN DRIVER NOTICED A VAPOR COMING OFF THE BACK OF THE TRAILER, THE DRIVER STOPPED AND WENT TO THE BACK OF THE TRAILER TO INVESTIGATE AND FOUND A CHEMICAL TOTE TANK HAD A BROKEN 2' VALVE AND THE CONTENTS HAD EMPTIED OUT. THE TANK HAD EVIDENTLY SHIFTED AND STRUCK OTHER CARGO BREAKING THE VALVE OFF. THE DRIVER CALLED AND REPORTED THE INCIDENT AND COULD NOT TELL WHERE THE CHEMICAL HAD ACTUALLY SPILLED SINCE THE ROADWAY WAS WET FROM THE SNOW MELTING. WE ARE FITTING THE MATERIALS TRUCKS AND TRAILERS WITH STRAPS TO SECURE THE LOADS, SIDE BOARDS WHERE USED PREVIOUSLY FOR SECURITY BUT THIS IS EVIDENTLY INSUFFICIENT, AND ACTIONS ARE BEING TAKEN TO PREVENT FUTURE ACCIDENTS FROM OCCURRING.

CARTON (CONTAINING FLAMMABLE LIQUID IN GLASS GALLON JUG) WAS ACCIDENTALLY DROPPED (SLIPPED OUT OF HANDS) DURING LOADING- COMPLETE LOSS OF CHEMICAL, DUE TO GLASS JUG BREAKING. SPILL WAS CLEANED UP WITH OIL DRI AND WAS REPORTED TO THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL & SAFETY SUPERVISOR AT THE GENERAL OFFICE.

column168: DRIVER PULLED INTO A REST AREA FOR TIRE CHECK AND NOTICED LIQUID DRIPPING FROM THE REAR OF TRAILER. EMERGENCY RESPONDERS FOUND ONE LEAKING DRUM OF MIPA. IT WAS OVERPACKED AND THE VEHICLE AND PAVEMENT CLEANED BY A FOR-HIRE CONTRACTOR, (CHEMTRON INC.) THE OVERPACKED DRUM WAS RETURNED TO VOPAK'S MEDINA SITE FOR RECOVERY OF REMAINING PRODUCT.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS RECOVERED USING ABSORBENT, DRUMMED AND TRANSPORTED TO VOPAKS MEDINA SITE FOR PROFILING AND DISPOSAL. THE TRAILER AND PAVEMENT WAS DEEMED PROPERLY CLEANED BY ONSITE PUCO AND HIGHWAY PATROL REPRESENTATIVES AND ALLOWED TO CONTINUE ON TO DESTINATION. INVESTIGATION REVEALED TWO SMALL PUNCTURES IN DRUM BOTTOM, PROBABLY FROM PROTRUDING NAILS ON THE STORAGE PALLET AT LOAD POINT.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING, A FIBERBOARD BOX CONTAINING ONE, FIVE GALLON PLASTIC BLADDER WAS PUNCTURED BY A FORKLIFT AT THE HALFWAY MARK OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY TWO GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION AND ABSORBENTS. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, DAMAGED BOX AND DAMAGED BLADDER WERE PLACED INTO A FIFTY-FIVE GALLON METAL RECOVERY DRUM, WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING, ONE DAMAGED FIFTY-FIVE GALLON METAL DRUM WAS DISCOVERED IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY TWENTY GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. THE DAMAGE WAS DUE TO A FORKLIFT PUNCTURE. TERMINAL PERSONNEL USED GLOVES AND MASKS TO PLACED THE DAMAGED DRUM INTO A SIXTY-FIVE GALLON POLY OVERPACK DRUM. HAZMAT ONE OF WICHITA, KS WAS DISPATCHED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. FURTHER CLEANUP DETAILS WILL BE PROVIDED UPON INVOICING. HAZMAT ONE PLACED THEIR CLEANUP MATERIALS INTO A THIRTY-FIVE GALLON METAL RECOVERY DRUM WHICH IS BEING HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS FORWARDED ON TO THE CONSIGNEE ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. DURING A ROUTINE INSPECTION OF THE TRAILER UPON ARRIVAL AT THE TERMINAL, ONE LEAKING FIFTY-FIVE GALLON PLASTIC DRUM WAS DISCOVERED AT THE HALF MARK OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY HALF A GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO THE LOAD SHIFTING, CAUSING THE DRUM TO TIP OVER AND FREE PRODUCT TO LEAK FROM THE BUNG. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION, AMPHOMAG, A DUSTPAN AND A BROOM. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A NINETY-FIVE GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE LEAKING DRUM AND THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING SHIPPER INSTRUCTIONS. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: DRIVER ARRIVED AT CUSTOMER BULK PLANT AND HOOKED UP UNLOADING LINES TO CUSTOMER TANK PER HIS INSTRUCTION AND PROCEEDED TO UNLOAD. DURING THE COURSE OF UNLOADING, AN EMPLOYEE OF THE BUSINESS NOTICED PRODUCT OVERFLOWING FROM THE TOP OF UG STORAGE TANK AND ALERTED THE DRIVER ABOUT THE PROBLEM. THE DRIVER STOPPED THE FLOW OF PRODUCT INTO  THE TANK AND THE OVERFLOW PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED IN THE CONCRETE CONTAINMENT AREA. THE DRIVER REPORTED THE INCIDENT TO DISPATCH OFFICE AND MONITORED THE SITUATION AT THE BULK PLANT. AFTER A PERIOD OF ABOUT 45-60 MINUTES, THE PRODUCT IN THE CONTAINMENT AREA LEAKED OUT ALONG THE SIDES OF THE CONCRETE WALL. THIS INCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO THE NRC, SERC AND LOCAL DEQ. REMEDIATION OF THE SITE STARTED IMMEDIATELY AND THE CONTAMINATED SOILS WERE REMOVED. UNDER THE GUIDANCE OF THE LOCAL DEQ AND AN ENVIRONMENTAL FIRM, RESIDUALS MANAGEMENT INC (RMI)- BOISE,ID, THE SITE HAS BEEN FULLY REMEDIATED AND BACKFILLED. THIS LOCATION HAD 2 TANKS ON THE SAME MANIFOLDED PRODUCT LINE. THE DRIVER HAD NEGLECTED TO SWITCH A QUARTER TURN VALVE TO THE PROPER TANK PRIOR TO STARTING THE UNLOADING PROCESS. SUBSEQUENTLY, THE #2 DIESEL HE WAS UNLOADING WENT INTO THE #1 DIESEL TANK WHICH RESULTED IN THE TANK OVERFLOWING THROUGH THE TOP VENT. SINCE THE INCIDENT, THE DRIVER HAS BEEN REPRIMANDED FOR NOT FOLLOWING PROCEDURES THAT WOULD HAVE PREVENTED THIS INCIDENT

column168: TC DUPX29406, LOAD HEXAMETHLYENEDIAMINE SOLID WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING BY TRAIN CREW UPON INVESTIGATION OF DERAILMENT OF TRAIN Q61415 NEAR HUFF ROAD OVERPASS IN ATLANTA.  AT APPROXIMATELY 2:15 PM.  SEVEN RAIL CARS WERE INVOLVED IN THE DERAILMENT.  (DUPX 29433, LOAD HEXAMETHYLENEDIAMINE; ACFX59397, ACFX53752 AND CSXT201573, LOADED HOPPER CARS OF ADIPIC ACID; AMCX66466, LOADED HOPPER OF PLASTIC PELLETS AND CSXT24176, EMPTY HOPPER). LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONDERS WERE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED VIA 911, AS WELL AS GEORGIA EMA, FULTON COUNTY EMA AND THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC.  CSX TRANSPORTATION EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTORS WERE ALSO DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE.  CSX PERSONNEL ALONG WITH FIRE DEPARTMENT REPRESENTATIVES AND CONTRACTORS.  ALSO RESPONDED TOO ASSESS THE LEAK.  PRODUCT LEAKED FROM THE FLANGE CONNECTION OF THE VAPOR VALVE OF T/C, WITH AN ESTIMATED RELEASE OF LESS THAT 600 GALLONS.  CSX HAZMAT CONTRACTORS MADE ENTRY AND TIGHTENED THE FOUR FLANGE BOLTS (APPROX. 1 TURN EACH) AND THE LEAK STOPPED.  PRIOR TO UPRIGHTING THE TANK CARS, PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED FROM THE DERAILED CARS INTO THREE EMPTY TANK CARS.  SOME PRODUCT HAD FLOWED INTO A DITCH ALONG THE TRACKS APPROXIMATELY 100 YARDS FROM THE TANK CAR.  CSX ENVIRONMENTAL PERSONNEL WORKING WITH STATE AND USEPA ENVIRONMENTAL OFFICIALS, ASSESSED THE SPILL AND DAMMED THE DITCH TO PREVENT FURTHER FLOW OF THE PRODUCT.  RECOVERY EQUIPMENT WAS PLACED AT THE DAM SITE TO RECOVER PRODUCT IN THE DITCH AND CITRIC ACID WAS USED TO NEUTRALIZE THE SPILLED MATERIAL.  A WATER FLUSH WAS PROVIDED BY THE FIRE DEPT TO FLUSH OUT AND NEUTRALIZE REMAINING PRODUCT IN THE DITCH.  THE CAUSE OF THE DERAILMENT AND RELEASE IS BEING INVESTIGATED BY CSX TRANSPORTATION.

A CSXT CAR INSPECTOR  OBSERVED TANK CAR ACFX82580 VENTING FROM THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE. THE WAYCROSS, GA FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED AND UPON ARRIVAL AND ASSESSMENT APPLIED WATER TO THE OUTSIDE OF THE TANK CAR TO COOL IT.  THIS WATER APPLICATION STOPPED THE VENTING. THE VENTING WAS CAUSED BY OVERLOADING OF THE CAR. THE CAR WAS MOVED TO AN ISOLATION TRACK AND 300 GALLONS OF LIQUID WAS TRANSFERRED FROM THE CAR. AFTER A PRESSURE CHECK, THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION.

column168: I WAS DISPATCHED TO AN INJURY ROLL OVER TRAFFIC COLLISION, E/B I-80 ON THE DIRT FILL PORTION OF THE CAUSEWAY AT 1102 HOURS.  I RESPONDED FROM ENTERPRISE BLVD. AT I-80.  WHILE ENROUTE, I COPIED VIA SCANNER (DAVIS FIRE CHANNEL) THAT THE VEHICLE WHICH OVERTURNED WAS A TRUCK THAT HAD A PLACARD #2187.  I INFORMED CHP DISPATCH OF THE PLACARD NUMBER AND REQUESTED INFORMATION AS TO WHAT THE TRUCK MAY BE CARRYING.  UPON MAKING MY TURN AT WEBSTER U/C, I COPIED VIA SCANNER THE TRUCK WAS NOW ON FIRE AND WAS CARRYING CARBON MONOXIDE.  I ADVISED DISPATCH THAT TRAFFIC WAS SLOWING AND STOPPING AND THAT I WOULD STOP ALL E/B I-80 TRAFFIC ON THE CAUSEWAY APPROXIMATELY 1500 FT PRIOR TO THE COLLISION SCENE (1109 HOURS).  I REQUESTED NOTIFICATION OF CAL-TRANS AND ASSISTANCE OF OTHER UNITS AND TO ALSO CLOSE THE W/B LANES OF I-80.  WHILE I WAS STOPPING THE TRAFFIC DAVIS FIRE DEPT AND AMR AMBULANCE PASSED MY CLOSURE AND RESPONDED TO THE SCENE. I REQUESTED DISPATCH TO HAVE A UNIT RELIEVE ME SO I COULD GET CLOSER TO THE SCENE AND CONTACT FIRE AND MEDICAL PERSONNEL.  I ARRIVED ON SCENE AT APPROXIMATELY 1121 HOURS.  UPON ARRIVAL I CONTACTED DAVIS FIRE CHIEF JACK HICKLEY WHO INFORMED ME THAT THE TRUCK WAS CARRYING CO2 AND THE TANK WASN'T ON FIRE, JUST VENTING INTO THE AIR, NO CONTACT WITH THE GROUND.  I WALKED TO THE AMR AMBULANCE AND WAS HANDED THE TRUCK DRIVER'S, DRIVER'S LICENSE AND WAS INFORMED BY MEDICAL PERSONNEL THAT THEY NEEDED TO TRANSPORT THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY.  I ADVISED THEM (AMR) TO CONTINUE WITH THE VICTIM TRANSPORT.  ALL TIMES, SPEEDS AND MEASUREMENTS ARE APPROXIMATIONS. MEASUREMENTS WERE MADE BY ROLL-A-METER, ODOMETER AND ESTIMATION.

column168: OUR EMPLOYEE LOADED A TRACTOR/TANK AT A BULK TERMINAL FACILITY PREPARATORY TO DELIVERING GASOLINE TO A RETAIL LOCATION.  AS HE PULLED FROM THE TERMINAL PROPERTY ONTO THE ROADWAY, HE OBSERVED A TRAIL OF LIQUID FROM HIS VEHICLE.  UPON EXITING AND INSPECTION, HE DISCOVERED A BENT MUD FLAP BRACKET ON THE TRACTOR HAD PUNCTURED THE FILL/DROP TUBE AND THE EMERGENCY SHUT OFF VALVE ON HIS TRAILER.  HE IMMEDIATELY ATTEMPTED TO SHUT OFF THE COMPARTMENT THAT CONTAINED 2,750 GALLONS OF GASOLINE BUT WAS UNABLE TO STOP THE FLOW.  HE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED TERMINAL MANAGEMENT WHO CALLED THE SPEEDWAY FIRE DEPARTMENT.  UPON ARRIVAL OF THE SPEEDWAY FIRE DEPARTMENT, THEY APPLIED DUCT TAPE TO THE PUNCTURED TUBE AND APPLIED FOAM TO THE TRAILER AND AREA OF THE ASPHALT STREET WHERE APPROXIMATELY 1,375 GALLONS OF GASOLINE HAD FLOWED.  THE SPEEDWAY DEPARTMENT RECEIVED ASSISTANCE FROM THE WAYNE TOWNSHIP FIRE DEPARTMENT WHO CONTROLLED THE FLOW OF PRODUCT TO AN AREA OF APPROXIMATELY 270'' X 24'.  THE SPILLED FUEL FOLLOWED LOCAL TOPOGRAPHY OF THE AREA AND PROCEEDED TOWARDS A STORM SEWER DRAIN LOCATED ON EACH SIDE OF OLIN AVENUE.  THE STORM SEWER'S PATH TRANSECTED WESTWARD THROUGH THE TERMINAL PROPERTY TOWARDS LITTLE EAGLE CREEK WHERE THE STORM SEWER ULTIMATELY OUTFALLS.  ABSORBENT BOOMS WERE PLACED AT THE POINT OF OUTFALLS AND FURTHER DOWNSTREAM.  AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR, NORTH AMERICAN CONSTRUCTION COMPANY, INC., SPREAD ABSORBENT MATERIAL OVER THE AREA OF THE ASPHALT STREET.  THEY UTILIZED A VACUUM TRUCK AND VACUUMED POOLS OF PRODUCT, FOAM AND WATER.  THEY THEN POWER WASHED AND SQUEEGED THE ENTIRE AREA.  THE SPEEDWAY FIRE DEPARTMENT INJECTED THE STORM WATER SEWER SYSTEM WITH APPROXIMATELY 2500 GALLONS OF WATER IN AN ATTEMPT TO FLUSH OUT ANY RESIDUAL PRODUCT THAT MIGHT HAVE COLLECTED.  ANOTHER EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR, SPILL RECOVERY OF INDIANA, COLLECTED THE DISCHARGE AT THE CREEK.  THE STORM DRAINS AND CREEK WERE INSPECTED OVER THE NEXT NINE DAYS TO ENSURE SAFETY.

column168: UPON ARRIVAL AT THE WELL LOCATION, COMPANY DRIVER NOTICED THAT THE INNER SLEEVE HOLDING THE PERFORATING CHARGES TO THE PERFORATING GUN HAD VIBRATED FORWARD AND BROKEN OFF, A CHECK DETERMINED THAT 8 (EIGHT) SHAPED CHARGES HAD FALLEN OUT OF THE GUN.  LOCAL AUTHORITIES WERE NOTIFIED AND A SEARCH WAS BEGUN.  DURING THE NEXT 24 HOURS 6 OF THE 8 CHARGES WERE RECOVERED (2 HAVE NEVER BEEN FOUND). CORRECTIVE ACTIONS INCLUDE THE INSTALLATION OF "SUBS" IN THE GUN BODIES THAT "LOCK" THE ALIGNMENT SLEEVE IN THE GUN, PREVENTING MOVEMENT.  ALSO, THE TRAILERS USED TO TRANSPORT JET PERFORATING GUNS HAVE BEEN NOTIFIED TO PREVENT FORWARD MOVEMENT.

THE DRIVER DID EXACTLY AS TOLD AND ADVISED HIS ARM NO LONGER BURNED. THE CONSIGNEE ACCEPTED THE FREIGHT AND CLEANED THE CARRIER'S TRAILER, USING PROPER PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT.

column168: FILE 2190 F & D, SHIPPER: CN RAIL, AWB# YWG 4011102955 PPS.  ON 03/15/2002 AT 2:35 A SPILL WAS REPORTED OF A PACKAGE LEAKING AND EMITTING A FUEL TYPE ODOR IN SECONDARY 6 OF BUILDING "C" OF OUR SORT HUB FACILITY LOCATED AT 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO, 45177.  PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS ELWOOD BOHL AND JEFFERY KIDDER RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL THEY DONNED THEIR PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND APPROACHED THE PACKAGE IN QUESTION NOTING THAT THE PACKAGE WAS OVER 3/4 SATURATED BY WHAT APPEARED TO BE A PETROLEUM BASED PRODUCT.  THE PACKAGE DIMS WERE 15 3/4 X 13 X 12 3/4 THE BOX WAS A MACDONALD'S FRENCH FRIED POTATO BOX.  THE SPILL TECHNICIANS OPENED THE BOX AND DISCOVERED A PART THAT WAS WRAPPED IN BUBBLE WRAP AND A PLASTIC BAG HAD BEEN LEAKING THROUGH TWO OPEN HOLES IN WHAT APPEARED TO BE THE TOP OF THE PART.  ALSO THEY NOTED A MANUFACTURES TAG ON THE TOP OF THE PART THAT STATED PARAGON STANDARD LOCOMOTIVE FUEL PUMP, MODEL #2600-AC.  THE SPILL TECHNICIANS PLACED THE SHIPMENT INTO TWO LARGE PLASTIC BAGS WITH AN ABSORBENT PAD AND REMOVED IT FROM THE AREA.  THE SHIPMENT WAS TAKEN TO THE HAZ MAT SORT BUILDING AND PLACED IN A UN SPECIFICATION SALVAGE DRUM THEN PUT INTO THE HAZ MAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.  THERE WERE TWO EMPLOYEES INVOLVED BY INHALATION, BUT DID NOT REQUIRE ANY MEDICAL TREATMENT OR MEDICAL FOLLOW UP, THEY BOTH RETURNED TO WORK IMMEDIATELY AFTER THE SHIPMENT WAS REMOVED FROM THEIR WORK AREA. THIS WAS AN UNDECLARED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SHIPMENT.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS, OR A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO OR ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THE CONTENTS WAS A REGULATED MATERIAL.  CLEAR OF SCENE: 02:53

FILE 2189 F & D, SHIPPER: AIRBORNE EXPRESS, AWB# DEN 6600280588 WLA.  ON 03/12/2002 AT 03:20 AN ODOR OF KEROSENE WAS REPORTED AT GATE D-22 IN THE LOWER BELLY COMPARTMENT WHILE BEING LOADED OF ABX AIRCRAFT N825AX LOCATED AT OUR FACILITY, ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OH, 45177. PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS CECILA HICKEY, RANDY WILLIAMS AND KEVIN GAREN RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL THEY DONNED THEIR PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND USED A GAS DETECTION DEVICE TO DETERMINE WHERE THE ODOR WAS COMING FROM.  AS THE SPILL TECHNICIANS BEGAN GOING THROUGH THE FREIGHT IN THE LOWER COMPARTMENT THEY DISCOVERED A LARGE BOX THAT POSSIBLY COULD HAVE A KEROSENE ODOR.  THE PACKAGE WAS A MANUFACTURERS BOX DIPICITING A PICTURE OF A KEROSENE HEATER AND STATING THAT THE HEATER WAS A DYNA-GLO 23,000 BTU CONVECTION TYPE PORTABLE KEROSENE HEATER.  THE SPILL TECHNICIANS REMOVED THE SHIPMENT FROM THE AIRCRAFT COMPARTMENT AND IT WAS FOUND TO BE THE SHIPMENT EMITTING THE ODOR.  ONCE THE SHIPMENT WAS OPENED IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT IT HAD LEAKED APPROXIMATELY 1 1/2 OUNCES OF KEROSENE AND APPROXIMATELY 1 OUNCE WAS STILL IN THE TANK.  DIGITAL PICTURES WERE TAKEN OF THE CUTER PACKAGE AND THE HEATER THEN THIS WAS PLACED INTO A UN SPECIFICATION SALVAGE DRUM AND PLACED IN OUR HAZMAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.  OTHER THAN THE MANUFACTURES PICTORIALS AND ADVERTISEMENT ON ALL FOUR SIDES OF THE PACKAGE THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS OR SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO OR ACCOMPANYING THE SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THAT THE HEATER CONTAINED A REGULATED MATERIAL.  CLEAR OF SCENE: 03:33.

column168: THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE INBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE DISCREPANCY WAS DISCOVERED. THE SHIPMENT HAD JUST TRANSITED INTO THE FEDEX SEATLLE RAMP FACILITY FROM BELLINGHAM, WASHINGTON ON FEDEX FEEDER FLT- 7696(BLI-SEA). THE PACKAGE WAS EXHIBITING STAIN AND A GASOLINE ODOR. THE PACKAGE WAS ISOLATED, OPENED AND EXAMINED TO REVEAL A SMALL LAWN MOWER ENGINE. THE ENGINE WAS NOT DRAINED OF FUEL PRIOR TO BEING SHIPPED. THERE WERE NO HAZMAT MARKINGS OR LABELS EXHIBITED ON THE OUTER SURFACE OF THE PACKAGE NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS OFFERED WITH THE SHIPMENT. THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO THE F.A.A. FOR INVESTIGATION. TELEPHONE NOTIFICATION WAS MADE TO SPECIAL AGENT JANA NICASTRO/FAA/SEA/CASFO AT 16:30  (CST) ON 03/22/2002.

ON MARCH 6, 2002 AT 10:15 AM WE WERE MAKING A DELIVERY TO THE RESIDENCE AT R.R. 1 BOX 298, HOLLIDAYSBURG, PA 16648.  AS HE WAS FILLING THE TANK OUR DRIVER MICHAEL SOBETSKY STATED THAT HE CONTINUED TO HEAR A STEADY VENT WHISTLE THROUGHOUT THE ENTIRE DELIVERY, AND THROUGH OUT THE DELIVERY NO FUEL OIL BACKED UP INTO THE FILL PIPE OR INTO THE VENT PIPE.  THE RESIDENT HAD STATED THAT THEY WERE RATHER LOW ON FUEL WHEN THEY ORDERED THE DAY BEFORE.  SO UNTIL OUR DRIVER'S METER EXCEEDED TWO HUNDRED AND SIXTY GALLONS (HE HAD VIEW OF THE METER ON THE TRUCK FROM THE FILL PIPE) HE HAD NO REASON TO BE ALARMED.  AT THIS POINT HE WENT TO THE FRONT DOOR & HAD THE RESIDENT CHECK ON THE TANK IN THE BASEMENT.  THAT IS WHEN THEY DISCOVERED THE LEAKING FUEL TANK.  MICHAEL SOBETSKY TOOK IMMEDIATE ACTION TO STOP THE LEAKING AND BLOCK THE FLOW OF HEATING OIL TOWARD A FLOOR DRAIN.  AT 10:45 A.M. HE THEN CALLED ME AT OUR OFFICE AND I IMMEDIATELY GATHERED MATERIALS AND WENT TO THE SCENE.  AT 11:25 A.M. I ARRIVED AT THE SITE AND TOGETHER WE RECOVERED ABOUT 150 GALLONS IN OTHER CONTAINERS.  WE WORKED TOGETHER TO STOP THE SPILL AND NEUTRALIZE THE AFFECTS OF THE SPILLED PRODUCT.  AT 12:15 P.M. I THEN CALLED OUR COMPANY'S NATIONAL SPILL RESPONSE NUMBER, THEY IN TURN NOTIFIED ALL OF THE PROPER AUTHORITIES.  I THEN CALLED SUGAR RUN SPILLS TO BE THE CONTRACTOR TO DO THE SPILL REMEDIATION WORK, IN THE BASEMENT, ON THE RIVER BANK, AND IN THE RIVER.  I THEN CALLED TO MAKE ARRANGEMENTS FOR ANOTHER FUEL TANK TO BE INSTALLED, AND THE REUSEABLE FUEL TO PUMPED BACK INTO THE NEW TANK.

SECURITY ENVIRONMENTAL OFFICER ANDINO WAS CONTACTED TO AA BAGROOM BY ENVIRONMENTAL OFFICER/CSM ALBERT REGARDING BAG FOUND TO BE SPILLING A LIQUID SUBSTANCE. EC WAS NOT ABLE TO CONTACT PASSENGER TO INVESTIGATE FURTHER DUE TO DELAYED FLIGHT AND PASSENGER IN TRANSIT TO NEW DEPARTURE GATE. EC FOUND SEVERAL UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS IN THE CHECKED LUGGAGE AND CONTACTED THE SEO TO ASSIST IN TALKING TO PASSENGER. ITEMS VERIFIED IN BAG WERE TWO 6 OZ BOTTLES OF ACETONE, FOUR 12.5 OZ AEROSOL CANS OF FURNITURE POLISH AND THREE 32 OZ BOTTLES OF AMMONIA WINDEX. OF THE THREE BOTTLES OF WINDEX CLEANER 2 BOTTLES HAD SPILLED 48 OZ OF THE SUBSTANCE. PASSENGER WAS AT A LATER TIME FOUND AT THE NEW DEPARTURE GATE AND ADVISED OF FAA REGULATIONS, REPORTING REQUIREMENTS AND POSSIBLE FINES DUE TO THE UNDECLARED ITEMS IN HIS CHECKED BAG. THE BAG HAD NO APPARENT TRIGGERS. THE BAG IS BEING HELD WITH ALL OTHER RESTRICTED ARTICLES FOR FAA INVESTIGATION. THE UNRESTRICTED ITEMS WILL BE FORWARDED IF BAG IS RELEASED BY THE FAA. NO INJURY OR PROPERTY DAMAGED OCCURRED AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT.

column168: LANE A SEKAVEC, MANGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS NOTIFIED BY THE CAR FOREMAN AT 18TH STREET YARD OF A LEAKING ALCOHOL CAR. MR.SEKAVEC AND CHRISTI HORNICK PROCEEDED TO 18TH STREET WHERE MR. SEKAVEC EXAMINED THE CAR. INITIAL OBSERVATION SHOWED LIQUID PRODUCT RUNNING DOWN THE SIDE OF THE CAR AND ACROSS A ROAD TO A GRAVEL PARKING AREA. UPON OPENING THE WEATHER COVER, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE THREE-INCH LIQUID VALVE WAS OPEN AND THE PLUG FOR THE VALVE WAS LYING NEXT TO THE VALVE. THE VALVE WAS CLOSED, THE PLUG INSTALLED AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION. THE ALCOHOL THAT  HAD ACCUMULATED IN THE PARKING AREA WAS PUMPED INTO FOUR DRUMS. AFTER THE CAR WAS MOVED, THE AREA UNDERNEATH THE CAR REMEDIATED BY REMOVING THE CONTAMINATED SOIL BETWEEN THE TIES AND ON THE DOWNHILL SIDE OF THE ROAD. THE SOIL WAS PLACED INTO A HAZ-WASTE ROLL-OFF BOX FOR DISPOSAL FOLLOWING ANALYSIS. SAMPLES WERE ALSO TAKEN OF THE LIQUID FOR ANALYSIS. CLEAN ROCK WAS THEN PLACED INTO THE AREA AND THE TRACK RELEASED.

column62: Abrasion; Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: DANNY,MANAGER OF YARD OPERATIONS, REPORTED CONTAINER MSCU 288631, A LOAD MARKED AS A MARINE POLLUTANT, LOCATED AT THE RAMP IN SPACE WHITE 200, WAS OBSERVED DRIPPING AN UNKNOWN SUBSTANCE. DEAN COPPER, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. MANAGER COOPER FOUND THAT LESS THAN ONE GALLON OF PRODUCT HAD SPILLED FROM THE RIGHT REAR OF THE CONTAINER, ONTO THE PAVEMENT. THE LADING CONSISTED OF 55 GALLON DRUMS, DOUBLE STACKED, WITH CARDBOARD USED TO BILEVEL SEPARATION. MR.COOPER CONTACTED SCOTT WELLS, ETHYL CORP., RICHMOND, VA AND NOTIFIED HIM OF THE CONDITION OF THE LADING. TRANSLOADING ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CALLED IN TO SECURE THE CONTAINER AND HAVE IT GROUNDED ONTO PLASTIC AND ABSORBENT TO CONTAIN ANY ADDITIONAL LEAKING MATERIAL. AS THE MATERIAL WAS NOT  ACTIVELY LEAKING, IT WAS SECURED FOR THE NIGHT, WITH TRANSLOADING TO BE COMPLETED THE FOLLOWING MORNING. WHILE REMOVING THE DRUMS FROM THE CONTAINER, LOCATED ONE DRUM, TWO ROWS IN FROM THE REAR DOORS, ON THE RIGHT SIDEWALL, THAT HAD BEEN SET AGAINST A SIDE WALL 'D' RING DURING THE LOADING PROCESS. THE 'D' RING DENTED THE BOTTOM CHIME OF THE DRUM, CAUSING A SPLIT IN THE METAL, WHICH ALLOWED THE ENTIRE CONTENTS OF THE DRUM TO BE RELEASED DURING TRANSIT. ROUGHLY 20 GALLONS OF PRODUCT REMAINED ON THE FLOORING OF THE CONTAINER, WHICH WAS REMOVED FOR DISPOSAL. SEVERAL ADDITIONAL DRUMS WERE NOTED TO HAVE LOADING DAMAGE WHICH MADE THEM UNFIT FOR FURTHER TRANSPORT. THEY WERE PLACED INTO OVER PACK DRUMS FOR SECUREMENT AND ARE TO BE SHIPPED BACK TO THE MANUFACTURER PER THEIR REQUEST. DUE TO THE MATERIAL WICKING INTO THE WOOD FLOORING, THE LADING WAS TRANSFERRED TO CONTAINER TRIU 130123. THE LADING WAS PROPERLY SECURED, AND THE CONTAINER RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE. THE FLOORING IN THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER IS TO BE REMOVED AND PROPERLY DISPOSED.

column168: AT 1300HRS ON 3-7-02, CTS MGR LERCH RESPONDED TO REPORTED LEAKING TANK CAR DUPX 29211, LOCATED IN TRACK 15, ENGLEWOOD YARD, HOUSTON,TX. INITIAL REPORTS INDICATED THAT THE CAR WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP, AND MANAGER OF MECHANICAL MAINTENANCE RONNIE LEWIS WAS TAKING AN EMPLOYEE TO THE HOSPITAL FOR REPORTED INHALATION INJURY RESULTING FROM PRODUCT RELEASE. ADDITIONALLY, APPROXIMATELY 15 PEOPLE WERE EVACUATED FROM THE IMMEDIATE AREA UPON ARRIVAL, MGR LERCH NOTED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE TWO INCH LIQUID VALVE AT A RATE OF APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON AN HOUR  WITH NO POOLING OF PRODUCT. INSPECTION OF THE CAR REVEALED THE OPERATING HANDLE OF THE TWO INCH BALL VALVE TO BE PARTIALLY  OPEN, IN THE FOUR O'CLOCK POSITION AND THE TWO INCH PLUG TO BE LOOSE 1 1/4 TURNS. AFTER THE VALVE WAS CLOSED AND THE PLUG TIGHTENED, THE LEAK STOPPED. THE CAR WAS ALLOWED TO CONTINUE ONTO DESTINATION. THERE WERE NO DRAINS OR WATER WAYS IMPACTED AS THE RESULT OF THIS RELEASE, AND THERE WAS NO CLEAN-UP REQUIRED AS PRODUCT EVAPORATED UPON CONTACT WITH THE OUTSIDE ATMOSPHERE. AT APPROXIMATELY 1600 HRS, IT WAS LEARNED THAT THE TOXICOLOGICAL TEST RESULTS WERE NEGATIVE REGARDING THE EMPLOYEE TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL FOR THE REPORTED INHALATION INJURY. AT 0830 HRS ON 2-8-02,CTS MGR LERCH WAS CONTACTED BY MECHANICAL MANAGE SAL PEREZ WHO REPORTED ANOTHER EMPLOYEE WAS COMPLAINING OF FEELING ILL DUE TO THE RESIDUAL ODOR FROM THE CAR, BUT DID NOT WISH TO GO TO THE HOSPITAL. MGR LERCH CONTACTED THE SHIPPER IN AN EFFORT TO FIND AND ODOR NEUTRALIZER, HOWEVER THERE WAS NO KNOW MATERIAL. MGR LERCH THEN APPLIED FLOOR DRY TO THE SPILL SITE AND WET THE AREA DOWN WITH WATER TO ABSORB THE RESIDUAL ODOR. AT 1515HRS, MGR LERCH WAS ADVISED BY MR PEREZ THAT THE EMPLOYEE COMPLAINING EARLIER OF FEELING ILL WAS TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL FOR TOXICOLOGICAL TESTING.TEST RESULTS UNKNOWN AT THE TIME OF THIS REPORT NOTIFICATIONS: 3-7-02, SHIPPER: DUPONT DE NEMOURS EL, ERROL MCLAUGHLIN, HAZMAT TRANSPORTATION SPECIALIST; KEN MARTIN, SAFETY ENGINEER.

ON THURSDAY,3/14/02, THE UPRR TRAIN, LLM31-13 WAS INVOLVED IN A SIDE WIPE DERAILMENT WHILE DEPARTING THE YARD A T LIVONIA, LA. HOPPER CAR GACX 1650, A RESIDUE LAST CONTAINED SODIUM CHLORATE, WAS NOT DERAILED, HOWEVER THE TWO END CAPS ON THE BOTTOM OUTLETS WERE DAMAGED AND THE CAM LOCK FITTINGS WERE OPENED. A SMALL OF SLURRIED SODIUM CHLORATE WAS RELEASED FROM ONE OF THE OUTLETS. UPON NOTIFICATION UPRR MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, T.M. ROBINSON RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.ROBINSON CLOSED THE CAM LOCK FITINGS ON THE CAPS AND THIS STOPPED THE LEAK. THE SMALL AMOUNT OF SPILLAGE ON THE ADJACENT BALLAST WAS RINSED WITH WATER.

column168: FILE: 2193F & D SHIPPER: COSTCO WHOLESALE 489, AWB FTW 73040242273  ON OPERATIONS DATE, 3/21/2002 AT 13:47 A CALL WAS MADE THAT THERE WAS A PACKAGE WITH WHITE POWDER COMING FROM IT IN BUILDING "B" OF OUR SORT HUB FACILITY LOCATED AT 145 HUNTER DRIVER, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177. UPON ARRIVAL PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS CECILIA HICKEY AND DIANE RAMSDEN OBSERVED THE PACKAGE IN QUESTION AS HAVING A WHITE POWDER ON IT AND ON TWO SIDE OF THE OUTER PACKAGE WAS THE WORDS IN BOLD PRINT "KIDDE HOME PROTECTION-2 PACK FIRE EXTINGUISHES" AT THE TIME THEY REALIZED THAT POSSIBLY ONE OR BOTH O THE FIRE EXTINGUISHERS HAD DISCHARGED. ON THE SIDE IN A CLEAR POUCH WAS A COSTCO WHOLESALE RECEIVING/SHIPPING AUTHORIZATION SHOWING THAT THEY WERE BEING RETURNED DUE TO ONE WAS HALF EMPTY. THE PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS OPENED THE BOX AND FOUND THAT ONE OF THE TWO FIRE EXTINGUISHERS HAD IN FACT DISCHARGED DUE TO THE SAFETY PIN MISSING. THE SHIPMENT WAS DOUBLE BAGGED AND PLACED IN OUR SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS OR A SHIPPER'S  DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO OR ACCOMPANYING THE SHIPMENT  TO INDICATE ITS CONTENTS WERE A REGULATED MATERIAL.

2000 LB PLT OF ENVIRONMENTALLY HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCE ON PRO 201669392 WAS STAGGED ON DOCK, USK DSR RON FINCH WAS MOVING ALOADED PLT BY AND GOT TO CLOSE, SCRAPPING THE SIDE OF THE STAGED FREIGHT. THE GLANCING CONTACT TORE OPEN TWO 50 LB BAGS. UPON DISCOVERY A PHONE CALL WAS PLACED TO JEFF TURNER AND WAS INSTRUCTED TO CONTACT THE SHIPPERS RESPONSE PROVIDER. I CALLED CHEMTREC TALKED TO TOM FLORES, REPORT NO 03062002074. HE CALLED AN ADM REPRESENTATIVE. WE WERE INFORMED THAT THIS PRODUCT WOULD ONLY POSE AN ENVIRONMENTAL HAZARD IF LEAKED INTO A WATER SOURCE. THAT THE HAZARD LEVEL WAS VERY LOW. WE COULD PERFORM THE CLEANUP OURSELVES. THERE WAS ABSOLUTELY NO DANGER OF THE PRODUCT ENTERING A WATER SOURCE. WE RECOVERED THE LOST PRODUCT AND PLACED IT INTO A 5 GAL RECOVERY PAIL ALONG WITH TWO TORN OPEN BAGS. THE PAILS WERE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER. RON WAS SUSPENDED FROM FURTHER FORKLIFT OPERATION THAT NIGHT AND RECEIVED RETRAINING THE NEXT DAY.

ENVIRONMENTAL ENTERPRISES PERSONNEL REMOVED THE 55-GALLON DRUM OF CORROSIVE AND PLACED IT INTO A NEW 85-GALLON OVERPACK DRUM. THE TRAILER WAS THEN SPRAYED WITH WATER TO NEUTRALIZE THE CORROSIVE. EEI PERSONNEL PULLED THE TRAILER TO THEIR SHOP AND WASHED THE TRAILER DOWN UNTIL THE PH WAS NEUTRAL.

MR. TUCKER SPOKE WITH CONSOLIDATED FREIGHTWAYS CONCERNING THE SPILL. MR. TUCKER STATED HE WOULD CONTACT MR. BARNES, RSM FOR CF, AND BRIEF HIM OF THE SITUATION. MR. TUCKER REQUESTED WE PLACE THE DRUMS INTO A TRAILER AND ORDER POLY DRUMS TO OVERPACK THE PRODUCT. THE PRODUCT HAS NOT BEEN RELEASED ONTO THE FLOOR. MR TUCKER CONTACTED MR. HAAKE AND BRIEFED HIM OF THE SITUATION. MR HAAKE STATED HE WOULD PLACE THE CONTAINERS IN A TRAILER. MR HAAKE STATED HE WOULD ORDER THE POLY DRUMS FOR THE PRODUCT. 0930 MR. TUCKER CONTACTED MR. HAAKE STATED THE SHIPPER SHOULD BE ABLE TO ACCEPT THE DRUM BACK ONCE OVERPACKED.

EMI#15408 A CONSOLIDATED FREIGHTWAYS TRAILER WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING A PREPOLYMER CONTAINING ISOCYANATE FROM A TRAILER LOCATED IN THE CF-MOTOR TERMINAL. THREE TO FIVE-GALLON BUCKETS OF THE PRODUCT HAD BEEN CRUSHED AND WERE LEAKING. THERE WERE 103 PAILS OF THE PRODUCT. THE MECHANIC DISCOVERED THE PROBLEM AT ABOUT 1100 A.M. AND NOTIFIED THE DOCK MANAGER. THEY WERE PRODUCING A FUME SINCE THE NIGHT BEFORE AND THE DOORS OF THE TRAILER WERE OPENED TO AIR IT OUT. CONTAMINANT CONTROL FROM MATTHEW, NORTH CAROLINA WAS MOBILIZED. THE SITE WAS CLEANED UP AS BEST COULD BE DONE AS THE PRODUCT HAD PARTIALLY SET UP. MR LYMBURNER OF LYMTAL INTERNATIONAL, THE MANUFACTURER, SAID THAT POLYMERS WERE NO LONGER A HAZARD AFTER THEY WERE SET UP. THE WASTE AND RECOVERED PAILS WERE RETURNED TO THE MANUFACTURER.

EMI JOB#15298 TWO DRUMS OF SODIUM BICHROMATE APPEARED TO HAVE BEEN OVERFILLED AND RELEASED ABOUT A HALF CUP OF PRODUCT, WHICH SPILLED ON THE TOP TO THE DRUM, RAN DOWN THE SIDES AND A LITTLE PRODUCT WAS ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER. CNW ENVIRONMENTAL WAS MOBILIZED TO THE SCENE, THEY REPLACED THE DEFECTIVE BUNGES, WIPED DOWN THE DRUMS AND CLEANED THE PRODUCT FROM THE FLOOR. A THIRTY-GALLON DRUM OF WASTE WAS PRODUCED. WASTE SENT TO CYCLECHEM INC. IN NEW JERSEY FOR DISPOSAL.

column168: PASSENGER ANGEL RUIZ, WHO WAS TRAVELING SJU - DFW - LRD VIA AMERICAN AIRLINES ON MARCH 30, 2002, CHECKED BAGGAGE CONTAINING A 15 OZ FLAMMABLE AEROSOL PRODUCT IDENTIFIED AS KIWI CAMP DRY HEAVY DUTY WATER REPELLENT. AFTER ARRIVING ON FLIGHT AA633 SJU-DFW, THE BAG WAS FOUND SATURATED WITH THE MATERIAL WHILE IN-TRANSIT AT DFW AIRPORT, TX.  IT WAS SUBSEQUENTLY DETERMINED THAT THE AEROSOL PRODUCT HAD BEEN RELEASED DUE TO UNPROTECTED PRESSURE AGAINST THE VALVE WHICH CONTAINED WITHIN THE BAGGAGE.  THE ITEM WAS REMOVED FROM BAGGAGE AND RESIDUE CLEANED USING APPROPRIATE MATERIALS. AMERICAN AIRLINES CONDUCTS ONGOING EFFORTS TO TRAIN EMPLOYEES AND EDUCATE THE TRAVELING PUBLIC ON THE ISSUE OF HIDDEN DANGEROUS GOODS.  HOWEVER, THIS PASSENGER WAS SEPARATED FROM HIS BAGGAGE WHILE IN-TRANSIT DUE TO A STORM RELATED OPERATIONAL IRREGULARITIES AND NOTIFICATION WAS MADE VIA HIS TRAVEL AGENT.  A DISCREPANCY REPORT WAS FILED WITH LOCAL CASFO OFFICIALS.

column168: DAVE WILLOUGHBY, MANAGER YARD OPERATIONS, REPORTED AN ODOR WAS NOTICED FROM TANKCAR PROX 24003 LOCATED IN YARD 1 ON TRACK 11 AT THE DOLORES YARD.  NO PERSONNEL WERE INJURED.  DUFFY EXON, MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, WERE NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  MGR. EXON DETERMINED THAT THE PRODUCT LEAKED FROM THE LIQUID EDUCTION LINE.  HE ADVISED THAT THE CAMLOC CAP CAME OFF THE THE LIQUID LINE WHEN THE BOX WAS CLOSED, CAUSING THE HANDLE TO BEND AND OPEN THE CAMLOC CAP.  THE CAMLOC CAP WAS REINSTALLED AND THE LEAK STOPPED.  SHIPPER, STATE COUNTY, AND CHEMTREC NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Derailment; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: TRAIN MLIFW 10 WAS REPORTED DERAILED WITH AN UNKNOWN NUMBER OF RAILCARS IN UNKNOWN POSITIONS WITH A POSSIBLE FIRE INVOLVED AND AN INJURED ENGINEER. THE DERAILMENT WAS NEAR MILE POST 88 ON THE LITTLE ROCK SUB AND EMS AND FIRE UNITS WERE RESPONDING TO THE SCENE.  TIM O'BRIEN, REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED AND RESPONDED TO THE SCENE. STEVEN GUNN, YARD MASTER, REPORTED TANK CAR ACFX 71690, WHICH WAS LOADED WITH BUTYL ACRYLATES WAS DERAILED AND LEAKING.  CHEMTREC AND STATE NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ENTERED THE SCENE AND DETERMINED THAT THERE WAS A TWO TO THREE INCH TEAR IN THE TANK.  MGR. O'BRIEN ARRIVED ON THE SCENE AND TOGETHER WITH THE FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZMAT TEAMS ATTEMPTED TO STOP THE LEAK.  HE WAS ABLE TO SLOW THE RELEASE TO A NEAR STOP.  CONTAINMENT DIKES AND BOOMS WERE SET UP TO CONTAIN THE SPILLED PRODUCT.  VACUUM TRUCKS WERE USED TO COLLECT THE SPILLED PRODUCT.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: A UNION PACIFIC CAR DEPARTMENT EMPLOYEE REPORTED A LIGHT AMMONIA ODOR WAS RELEASED FROM TANKCAR GATX 91560 LOCATED AT DES MOINES YARD.  THE EMPLOYEE REPORTED THAT THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE OF ANY ACTIVE RELEASE AND THERE WERE NO INJURIES.  MARK REIMERS, REGIONAL, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND DISPATCHED REPRESENTATIVES FROM HYDRO-KLEAN ENVIRONMENTAL, A HAZMAT CONTRACTOR, TO INSPECT THE CAR.  UPON INSPECTION, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE PLUG ON THE "B" END LIQUID VALVE WAS LOOSE 2 FULL TURNS AND THE VALVE ITSELF WAS PARTIALLY OPEN.  THE CONTRACTOR REPRESENTATIVE CLOSED THE VALVE AND TIGHTENED THE PLUG, STOPPING THE LEAK.

DEAN METCALF, MANAGER OF MECHANICAL MAINTENANCE, REPORTED TANKCAR ACFX 73824 WAS LEAKING FROM THE DOME ONTO THE TANK CAR, WITH PRODUCT DRIPPING ONTO THE GROUND.  LARRY WILDER, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY RESPONDED.  DIDNEY, FLINT HILLS RESOURCES - SHIPPER, WAS CONFERRED WITH MGR. WILDER.  SIX EMPLOYEES WERE EVACUATED TO A RANGE OF TWO HUNDRED FEET FROM THE TANK CAR.  MGR. WILDER DONNED APPROPRIATE PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT TO MAKE REPAIRS TO THE TANK CAR.  MGR WILDER TIGHTENED ONE LOOSE BOLT ON THE EDUCATION LINE TWO TURNS.  MGR WILDER AND TRANSPORT ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICE DECONTAMINATED THE TOP AND SIDES OF THE TANKCAR.  THE GROUND UNDER THE TANKCAR WAS ALSO DECONTAMINATED.  THE TANK CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: ED MC NUTT, MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, REPORTED WHILE PERFORMING A QUARTERLY INSPECTION OF TANKCARS AT CENTENNIAL YARD, HE DISCOVERED TANKCAR GATX 062504 A LOAD OF LP GAS, LEAKING FROM BOTH LIQUID LINES AND THE VAPOR LINE, WHILE STATIONARY ON TRACK 101.  MR. MC NUTT ADVISED HE TIGHTENED ALL THREE LINES AND THE PLUGS, SECURING THE LEAKS, AND RELEASED THE TANKCAR FOR DESTINATION.  MR. MC NUTT REPORTED HE DISENGAGED THE SEAL ON THE DOME, REGISTERED TO FINA OIL, NUMBER 9179.  JEFF, CHEMTREC, WAS NOTIFIED.

DAVE, YARDMASTER, REPORTED TANK CAR GATX 17841 WAS LOCATED IN YARD 8 ON TRACK 9 AND WAS VENTING.  DAVE ADVISED HE HAD NOTIFIED CHEMTREC WHO ISSUED REPORT NUMBER 03292002054.  ERNIE SIROTEK, REGIONAL MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND CONFERRED WITH HARRY RODABOUGH, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, AND ALAN JENSEN, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS.  MR. RODABOUGH WAS RESPONDING WITH AN ETA OF TWO HOURS.  MR. SIROTEK REQUESTED CONTACT WITH A REPRESENTATIVE OF THE SHIPPER.  SID WHITE, COASTAL CHEMICAL - SHIPPER, CONTACTED RISK MANAGEMENT AND ATTEMPTS TO CONFER HIM WITH MR. SIROTEK WERE UNSUCCESSFUL.  AFTER INSPECTION, MGR RODABOUGH REPORTED THE TANKCAR HAD A LOOSE MANWAY COVER, WITH ONE SWING BOLT IN THE DOWN POSITION AND TWO OTHER LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT.  MR RODABOUGH TIGHTENED THE BOLTS AND THE LEAK STOPPED.

TIMOTHY O'BRIEN, REGIONAL MANAGER OF CHEMICAL AND TRANSPORTATION AND SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED OF TANK CAR COCX 290042 LEAKING FROM THE TOP AT THE SETTEGAST YARD (TRACK 316).  MR O'BRIEN RESPONDED AND FOUND THE TANKCAR HAD A MANWAY GASKET OUT OF POSITION AND LESS THAN GALLON OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  THE MANWAY GASKET WAS REPOSITIONED AND THE TANKCAR WAS SECURED AND RELEASED AT 05:31 AM.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: HAZ-MAT DESIGNATED RESPONDER LEAH CLOUSER ANSWERED A LEAKER CALL AT UNLOAD DOOR B.  BOX WAS IN TRAILER. IT APPEARED TO HER THAT UNLOADER PICKED UP BOX, SAW IT WAS LEAKING, PUT IT RIGHT DOWN  AND TOLD HIS SUPERVISOR SHE TRANSPORTED BOX TO THE HAZ-MAT CAGE. HERB PROCESSED INTO DMP. FOUND 1 OF 6 BOTTLES BIATROL HAD A LOOSE CAP.  CONTENTS DISSOLVED PARTS OF THE LABELS OF OTHER 5, SO THEY HAD TO BE PROCESSED. SIX (6) OTHER QUARTS OF OTHER (NON-HAZ-MAT) LIQUIDS WERE CLEANED AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.

column42: HYDROGEN PEROXIDE, AQUEOUS SOLUTIONS WITH NOT LESS THAN 20 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 40 PERCENT HYDROGEN PEROXIDE (STABILIZED AS NECESSARY)
column168: DECISION TREE AND THE RESPONSE SHEET FOR OXIDIZER USE TO PROCESS SPILL THROUGH DMP.  CLAY WAS USED TO CONTAIN AND ABSORB SPILL.  SCBA WASN'T USED DUE TO THE LACK OF AN IRRITATING ODOR AND BUILDING VENTILATION.  REST OF PARCEL SENT ON TO ITS DESTINATION.  RECOMMEND: CHECK BOTTLES FOR CUTS & LEAKS BEFORE SHIPPING.

column42: ETHANOL OR ETHYL ALCOHOL OR ETHANOL SOLUTIONS OR ETHYL ALCOHOL SOLUTIONS
column168: DECISION TREE AND THE RESPONSE SHEET FOR FLAMMABLES USED TO PROCESS SPILL THROUGH DMP.  CLAY WAS USED TO CONTAIN AND ABSORB SPILL SCBA WASN'T USED DUE TO THE LACK OF AN IRRITATING ODOR AND BUILDING VENTILATIONS.  REST OF PARCEL SENT ON ITS DESTINATION.  RECOMMEND: AN OUTER SEAL BE APPLIED AROUND CAP TO PREVENT CAP FROM LOOSING.

I RESPONDED TO A SPILL IN ONE OF THE TRAILERS. I USE THE DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET FOR ORM-D. RESPONSE SHEET FOR ORM-D HAD ME PERFORM A LITMUS TEST. THE LITMUS TEST READ PH 2 BALANCE RANGE. RESPONSE SHEET AND RESULT OF LITMUS TEST HAD ME USE RESPONSE SHEET FOR CORROSIVE LIQUID. RESPONSE SHEET FOR CORROSIVE LIQUID HAD ME CAREFULLY APPLY SODIUM BIOCARBONATE. I RE-TESTED THE CONTAMINATED MATERIAL TO RE-INSURE THAT THE PH BALANCE WAS WITH IN THE RANGE OF BETWEEN 6-9 CLAY ABSORBENT WAS ALSO USE TO CONTAIN THE CONTAMINATED MATERIAL. ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIAL WAS PLACE IN A LINED SPILL TRAY. ALL CONTAMIATED MATERIAL WAS THEN TAKEN TO THE DMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING. PROPER LOADING METHODS WOULD HAVE PREVENTED THE SPILL. THE REMAINING ITEMS WERE SENT BACK TO THE SHIPPER IN EXCELLENT CONDITION.

MR. GRAY HAMMOND, MANAGER OF LOADING AND UNLOADING AT THE L.A. CHEMICAL PLANT, REPORTED THAT HE NEEDED SOME HELP WITH A LEAKING TANKCAR, ACFX 84441.  INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE CAR WAS LEAKING FROM ONE OF THE BOLTS SECURING THE BOTTOM OUTLET ASSEMBLY TO THE BOTTOM OF THE CAR.  LEAK CONFINED TO A SLIGHT DRIP.  MR. HAMMOND HAD PLACED A BUCKET UNDER THE CAR TO CATCH THE PRODUCT.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE CAR WOULD NEED TO BE UNLOADED.  THIS WAS ACCOMPLISHED ON 3/25/2002.  THE CAR AS THEN SHOPPED FOR REPAIR.  THIS CAR WAS PROPERLY PLACARDED, BUT IMPROPERLY BILLED.  THE CONTENTS ACTUALLY IN THE CAR WAS FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS, NOS (METHYLISOBUTYLCARBINOL).  THE WEIGH BILL SHOWED THE CONTENTS AS CEMENT CLINKER GRINDING COMPOUND.  THE BILLING WAS CORRECTED.

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: ON MARCH 5, 2002 @ 21:00 TRACTOR OWNER, ROBERT R JACKSON WAS DRIVING HIS 1999 FREIGHT LINER CLASSIC AND PULLING FERRELLGAS TRAILER UNIT 7345 1997 MISSISSIPPI. THE DRIVER WAS ENTERING THE FERRELLGAS FACILITY ON HIGHWAY. 411 WHEN HE MISJUDEGED THE CLEARANCE OF THE DRIVEWAY CAUSING THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER TO ROLL OVER ON THE RIGHT SIDE. THE PROPANE IN THE TRAILER WAS OFFLOADED INTO 2 BOBTAILS AND 1 TRANSPORT TRAILER. THERE WAS A SMALL RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON OF PROPANE WHICH DISSIPATED INTO THE ATMOSPHERE. THERE WERE NO INJURIES, NO EVACUATIONS HIGHWAY 411 WAS CLOSED UNTIL THE TRACTOR TRAILER WERE UPRIGHTED THE GEORGIA HIGHWAY PATROL WAS ON SCENE. THE ACCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO THE DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION, MR CREWS REPORT #595724.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: MR. CLEDE WIDENER WAS PULLING TWO 1,000 GALLON AGRICULTURE NURSE TRAILER WEST ON COUNTY ROAD SS. THE REAR AXLE ON THE SECOND TRAILER FAILED CAUSING IT TO OVER TURN IN THE ROAD. THE GUARD PROTECTING THE VALVES WAS BROKEN ALLOWING THE VALVES TO CONTACT THE ROAD. 4,000 LBS OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA ESCAPED INTO THE AIR. COUNTY RD. SS WAS CLOSED FOR ABOUT AN HOUR. THIS INCIDENT TAKING PLACE IN A REMOTE RURAL AREA NO EVACUATION WAS NECESSARY. NO ONE WAS EXPOSED AND THE CONTENTS OF THE NURSE TRAILER WENT INTO THE AIR. THE REMAINING 18-NURSE TRAILERS AT THE BRISTOL LOCATION WERE INSPECTED AND NO PROBLEMS WITH THE AXLES WERE FOUND.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: ON MARCH 12TH 2002, BOASSO AMERICA, DETROIT DISPATCHED RICHARD LONG (DRIVER) TO DELIVER ONE(1) ISO CONTAINER TO BASF GREENVILLE FOR MARCH 13TH 2002 AT 15:00 (3:00PM EST) LOADED WITH APPROX 38,580 LBS OF MHOROMER (SEE ATTACHED MSDS.) ON MARCH 13TH 2002 RICHARD LONG DEPARTED THE BOASSO AMERICA DETROIT YARD AT 11:25 AM FOR HIS 3:00PM APPOINTMENT IN GREENVILLE OH AT THE BASF PLANT LOCATED AT 1175 MARTIN ST. GREENVILLE, OH (SEE ATTACHED LOG) AT APPROXIMENTALLY 14:45 A CALL WAS MADE INTO THE BOASSO AMERICA DETROIT FACILITY BY THE DRIVER (RICHARD LONG) TO ADVISE OF A ROLL-OVER ACCIDENT WHICH HAD OCCURRED AT APPROX 14:15 IN THE ENTRANCE OF BASF GREENVILLE PLANT (SEE ILLUSTRATION #2 ATTACHED) AT 15:00 THE TERMINAL MANAGER (KEN SLAVEN) DEPARTED THE BOASSO AMERICA DETROIT FACILITY IN ROUTE TO THE ACCIDENT SCENE IN GREENVILLE OHIO. DURING THE DURATION OF THE TERMINAL MANAGERS TRIP THE BOASSO AMERICA SAFETY DEPT. WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT (MR. JACK PENERIO SAFETY DEPT & MR TONY ORTEGO, DIRECTOR OF SAFETY FOR BOASO AMERICA). THE SAFETY DEPT INITIATED CALLS TO ECS INSURANCE WHICH IMMEDIATELY ACTIVATES OUR EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAMS LOCATED NATIONWIDE. ALSO DURING THE TERMINAL MANAGERS TRIP, CALLS WERE MADE TO GREENVILLE F.D TO COMMUNICATE INFORMATION REGARDING THE SPILL AND RESPONSE OF THE PRODUCT PER THE MSDS AS WELL AS APPROX. ARRIVAL TIMES OF THE HAZMAT RESPONSE TEAM TOW SERVICE AND TERMINAL MANAGERS APPROX. ARRIVAL TIME. MEANWHILE AT THE SCENE THE DRIVER (RICHARD LONG) WAS EVALUATED BY GREENVILLE FD FOR INJURIES ETC AND TRANSFERRED TO WAYNE HOSPITAL FOR A COMPLETE PHYSICAL EXAM AS WELL AS A DRUG AND ALCOHOL TEST SET UP BY MR JACK PENERIO AND GLOBAL SAFETY AND SECURITY. THE GREENVILLE FD HAD EVACUATED AND SECURED A PERIMETER APPROX 300 BY 300 AROUND THE ACCIDENT SCENE AS WELL AS APPLIED ABSORBENT CHEMICAL SOCKS ON THE SRV LOCATED ON THE OVER TURNED ISO (SEE ILLUSTRATION#3) ALSO NOTED WIND DIRECTION WAS EAST BY SOUTH EAST.UPON THE ARRIVAL OF THE TERMINAL MANAGER FROM BOASSO AMERICA AT APPROX 17:50 IT WAS NOTED THAT THE PERIMETER WAS SET UP BY THE GREENVILLE F.D, ALSO ON SCENE WAS ONYX HAZMAT RESPONSE TEAM MR.SCOTT KISER OF THE PUBLIC UTILITIES COMMISSION OF OHIO, MR.DALE FARMER OF THE OHIO ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AGENCY, MR BEN HANISH WITH BASF SAFETY DEPT MR TERRY BREWER WITH BASF CONFINED SPACE SPILL RESPONSE TEAM AND SANDY'S TOWING/ROAD ONE WITH 3 THREE 50 TON WRECKERS (SEE ILLUSTRATION#3) ONCE IN PLACE THE TERMINAL MANAGER WITH BOASSO AMERICA PUT INTO ACTION THE PLACEMENT OF THE GREENVILLE F.D AND ONYX HAZMAT RESPONSE TEAM. ONYX SECURED AN AREA APPROX. 20' AROUND THE CONTAINER WITH A TRENCH, ABSORBENT SOCKS, CHEMICAL ABSORBENT PADS AND A PLASTIC LINER TO COVER THE GROUND AS WELL AS AN ADJACENT MAN-WAY COVER ONCE ONYX AND THE GREENVILLE F.D WERE COMPLETE AND IN PLACE, ROAD ONE WAS PUT INTO ACTION TO SEPARATE THE COVER TURNED TRUCK AND CHASIS FROM THE ISO. SEE ILLUSTRATION#4 UPON THE SEPARATION OF THE TRUCK AND CHASSIS, ONYX WAS PUT INTO PLACE TO INSURE
TANK RAN EMPTY AND CUSTOMER HAD ANOTHER COMPANY FILL TANK 2 DAYS BEFORE WE MADE DELIVERY AND OVERFILLED THE TANK.  DUE TO THE TANK BEING FULL ALREADY.
